post_text:
Do you know CASA's story?

In 2012, Jenna Leahy and Tacey Clayton Cundy met and immediately connected over the injustice they witnessed in their classrooms‚Äî even in the primary grades, students from low-income communities were not entering or progressing at the same rate as their higher income peers. Unfortunately, their experiences were not unique.

They decided to join forces, driven by a common mission‚Äîto raise the bar for education in Arizona. Their drive and persistence resulted in over $950,000 in start-up funding. Together, they visited over 50 of the top-performing schools across the country to learn best practices before submitting their charter application, which was unanimously approved in January of 2014.

After countless months of knocking on neighborhood doors in the stifling summer heat, CASA opened to a record number of students on August 4, 2014. Their vision, guided by overcoming the inequalities they had experienced in the early grades, is today a reality: a Phoenix school dedicated to closing the achievement gap‚ÄîCASA Academy.

CASA Academy believes that it is not enough to simply educate a child in the core academic areas; CASA scholars must also be equipped with character traits necessary to succeed in life.
CASA‚Äôs six core values are as follows:
Empowerment- We take ownership of our decisions, successes, and setbacks.
Perseverance- We work relentlessly to accomplish our goals.
Enthusiasm-We approach life with passion, energy, and excitement.
Respect-We honor the beliefs of others and treat others with kindness.
Integrity-We do the right thing even if no one is watching.
Responsibility-We are accountable for our actions and our work.

post_text: CASA Academy‚Äôs reading comprehension block focuses on the Arizona College and Career Ready Standards for comprehending literary and informational texts. post_text:
Why is CASA Academy here for you?

‚Ä¢ Before CASA opened, students in CASA‚Äôs community did not have the opportunity to attend a high performing elementary school. CASA Academy seeks to fill that void and dramatically change the life trajectory for the community‚Äôs youngest students by ensuring its students are on the path to graduation from college.

‚Ä¢ CASA Academy seeks to significantly alter the life paths of students in its community by providing an excellent education that sets students up to attend and graduate from high school and college.

‚Ä¢ By ensuring that students are academically proficient or excelling, are critical thinkers, and possess strong character traits, CASA Academy sets students up for success. When students leave CASA Academy, they will have developed the grit necessary to persevere in the face of challenges. This grit will enable students to successfully complete upper elementary, middle, high school and college, and will ensure that they become citizens who contribute to their communities in positive and transformational ways.

It is Arizona Charter Schools Week 2020! CASA Academy is proud to provide an education for our scholars rich in both rigorous academics and character development. Although we have been "closed" since mid-March, we have been working harder than ever behind the scenes to ensure our scholars still receive the best education possible! Our teachers have prepared daily academic lessons and messages for our scholars via video, we have checked in with every family at least once per week, and we have continued to provide daily food service to our families. At CASA, we love what we do and in particular, we love the scholars and families who we serve!

#AboveAndBeyondAZ #ClosedNotClosed #CharterSchoolsWeek

We have great news! New packets to supplement for reading comprehension and math will be available for pickup starting this Monday, 4/6! You can drive up to CASA to get them Monday- Friday between 8:30 a.m. and 9:30 a.m.

In addition to the packets, we also have a YouTube channel that features our CASA staff! You will be able to find lots of helpful videos here that will be updated each Friday, including a recorded lesson that can be paired with each day of the reading comprehension and math packets!

CASA families, this morning Governor Ducey and Superintendent Hoffman announced school closures in Arizona through the end of the school year. CASA will remain closed through the end of the school year and will reopen to scholars in August 2020 for the 2020-21 school year.

During the closure, we will continue to provide free meals for scholars and all children under 18. We will also be developing a plan for continued scholar learning during this time. We will share more information soon! Thank you.

Don't forget - CASA will be providing FREE meals to ALL children 18 and under through curbside pickup starting TOMORROW, Monday, March 23rd from 8:30 a.m. to 9:30 a.m. 2 meals will be given per child every day and all children receiving meals must be present.

When picking up the meals, please be on the lookout for signage with instructions. DO NOT get out of your car or park. Our staff on duty will not be answering any questions during this time. Please feel free to text or call Liliana Villasenor directly at 623-738-6071 with any questions or concerns. Thank you.

post_text: CASA Parents, Governor Ducey and Superintendent Hoffman announced today that all Arizona schools are to remain closed through April 10th. For this reason, CASA will be closed through April 10th. CASA will continue to serve FREE meals to all children under 18 years of age during the closure in our parking lot Monday-Friday, from 8:30-9:30 a.m. Please call or text Liliana Villasenor with the number of meals you will need if you haven't let us know already! She can be reached at 623-738-6071. We will continue to update our Facebook page with updates and information, so please check back regularly.

post_text: We are here to support you and your family during our school closure! Your child does NOT have to be enrolled at CASA to receive food. CASA will provide pickup stations in our parking lot. 2 meals will be given per child every day and all children receiving meals must be present. post_text: CASA Academy families, we wanted to let you know that yesterday, March 15th, Governor Doug Ducey and Superintendent of Public Instruction, Kathy Hoffman, announced the closure of all Arizona schools through March 27th due to the recent outbreak of COVID-19. Due to this guidance, CASA Academy will be closed through March 27th. We are working through all of the details right now (including meals for scholars and continued learning while school is closed), but wanted to let you know right away so that you can plan accordingly. Please note that public health officials recommend that scholars who are not at school stay at home to the greatest extent possible during this time. We will continue to closely monitor the recommendations from state officials and will keep you updated as we learn more. Please continue to check our facebook page for additional information and updates in the days to come. Thank you.
